##An oral history | what I learned after 14 days of isolation in my home in Singapore

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

Small children can be left alone and carefree, but it's not easy for US adults to be able to live a stable life in difficult times, thanks to the painstaking efforts of many behind the scenes.

Dictation | Mr. Chen

Organize East Kim Hee

I'm from Shanghai, where I had the opportunity to go to college 20 years ago because of a Ministry of Education Program, and I've lived and worked there ever since.

Because the Shanghainese "get clear" , so I am in the rules of Singapore is very suitable. I feel that under this new crown epidemic, the prevention and control measures in both places have their own merits and are very effective.

On January 18 this year, I took my wife and 2 year old daughter to my parents'home in Shanghai for the Spring Festival. I didn't see any news about the epidemic in Wuhan until I got back. In Shanghai a few days before the routine visit friends, go out to play. But soon after Wuhan announced that it was closing down the city, Shanghai also took urgent measures. For a time, all major public places and parks in Shanghai were closed. Although we are not nervous, but it is still an honest stay at home in the New Year.

While staying at home in Shanghai, he had to keep an eye on Singapore's response to the outbreak. Singapore was the first confirmed case on January 23, with the first few cases coming from tourists in Wuhan. At that time, some Singaporeans suggested that the government should ban all Chinese from entering the country. Speaking on behalf of the government at the time, Ministry of Education Ong Ye Kung called on Singaporeans to "understand one another and do unto others as you would have them do unto you. " He called on Singaporeans not to be intolerant of outsiders and to work together to tide over the difficulties. This gave us some reassurance that we would be back in years.

The three of US flew back to Singapore on January 27, the third day of the Lunar New Year, according to our itinerary. We wore masks to the Pudong airport, in Shanghai, in transit in Hong Kong, everyone we met was wearing masks and in a hurry. The conversation in the cabin became less, many people shut their eyes, the atmosphere is a bit heavy. But when I arrived at the Singapore Changi Airport in the early hours of the morning, I found no strict quarantine measures in place. I was particularly surprised that none of the officers at the airport's Customs Gate wore face masks.

When I was at the Shanghai airport, I received information that the Singapore government requires all schools, schools and kindergartens under the Ministry of Education to be placed in 14-day home quarantine for staff and students who have recently visited China.

For Staff, this is Leave of Absence, which is not deducted from salary and does not count as annual sick Leave, especially in the event of an outbreak. My daughter, who is in kindergarten, and I, who works at the school, have to do this as soon as we get back. Her Bank also requires all new employees to follow the absentee leave rules for safety reasons, as too many of its employees return to China for the New Year. The Singapore government subsidizes the company by 100 Singapore dollars (about 500 yuan) per person per day to reduce the company's losses.

So the three of us, after checking in with the company school, began the 14-day isolation experience at home. Fortunately, the original absenteeism leave only provided for less unnecessary travel, not an absolute ban on travel. The first thing we did at daybreak was to go to the supermarket and buy a lot of food and supplies to replenish the empty family stores. At that time in the supermarket supplies are abundant, the human is very few, wears the mask the human is to see few.

Together with what we saw at the airport, we experienced for the first time the different ways Singapore and China responded to the outbreak.

Home Quarantine for 14 days, the epidemic is getting worse

During the home quarantine, there is no impact on life, work can also be done online, the most difficult is my home children. Usually our family with a child style is often with out, the weekend two days are almost all early to go out late to play hi. She hadn't been out that long for as long as she could remember, and wasn't used to it. Therefore, at the beginning of the family this little "God beast" from time to time a little temper, asked us to play with her, every now and then also shouted to "accompany mom and Dad" to go downstairs around. These days, my husband and I play with all the toys we have in the house, and I can't help but take advantage of the lack of people around the house for a while. The child who did not watch cartoons before also got into the habit of watching half an hour every night at eight o'clock. Children learn very strong, less than 14 days, with mobile phone point to see video play to walk, and will suddenly use the remote control to turn off the parents to watch the energetic TV programs, in order to get attention.

Singapore's response to the outbreak has tightened as the number of patients in China has increased and more patients have been brought in:

Within days of my return, the absentee order was enforced on all companies.

On 7 February, on the 12th day of my home quarantine, Singapore raised the response level of the outbreak response system from yellow to orange as Singapore began to experience new pneumonia among its citizens who had not recently left the country, ordinary visitors who have been to China in the last 14 days (with the exception of Singaporean citizens and permanent workers in the new country) have been banned from entering the country.

Singaporeans are nervous for a time, there is a rush to buy supermarkets, shelves of necessities have been swept away. Fortunately, the "panic" buying lasted only a day or two, with the rapid replenishment of life and quickly subsided.

At the same time, the parties to prevent and control the epidemic more strictly. Take Home Quarantine, because I came back early, these days is no one to check, all by self-awareness. Those who arrived a week later than I did would receive two text messages from human resources early and late each day, and would have to respond immediately to confirm their location and determine whether they were quarantined at home. By February 14, the policy had been further tightened, with all home-bound people banned from leaving their homes and provided with basic necessities by government-arranged personnel.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Singapore imposed a 14-day home quarantine on Chinese visitors in mid-february

As more people were diagnosed, I chose to take off my mask

My home after the lifting of the quarantine, the children happy to go back to kindergarten, I also go to work as usual, the company has chosen to work, a week to the company, a week at home.

I started out wearing a mask, but I gave up after two weeks. On the one hand, not many people wear masks outside. I commute an hour a day, one way, bus to subway. As far as I can tell, on average, only about a third of the passengers on the train wear masks. The carriages were crowded as usual, and the passengers were close together. Occasionally hear a cough or two, I will inevitably have some doubts at first, there are passengers look at the sound, but no one has to avoid the action.

On the other hand, wearing a mask for a long time, there is breathing discomfort, throat dry feeling. Want to cough, but in full view of the public and afraid of causing unnecessary misunderstanding. For a long time, hold hard, the heart beat faster, people can not help but have a subtle psychological changes, will worry about whether they were hit, the more I think the more uncomfortable. Looking for an opportunity to take advantage of people do not pay attention to back off the mask, men breathe a few mouthfuls of unfiltered air, immediately comfortable, uncomfortable "symptoms" also disappear. After that, I gave up wearing a mask.

As for the daughter is even less happy, often just put on her, small hands immediately off. My heart is also big, according to the diagnosis record of infant patients rate is very low, and infant self-healing ability is stronger than adults information, simply do not wear it.

See here, unavoidably some friends will blame me "Buddha Department" . As it happens, Singapore's epidemic prevention policy has also been criticized by many domestic friends as the "Buddhist system. ".

This was initially linked to Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong's February 8 public address on the measures to deal with the outbreak. "If the number of confirmed cases continues to climb, " Lee Hsien Loong said in his speech, "close contact tracing will not help, and hospitals will not be able to cope if all suspected cases continue to be hospitalized and quarantined. Once that happens, and the death rate for the new coronavirus remains as low as for the common flu, the government will encourage people with only mild symptoms to see a family doctor and rest at home. Only the elderly, children and those with other complications are admitted in order to pool resources."

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Lee Hsien Loong told the public to get it right

In addition, the government should deal with the shortage of face masks. The most effective way to prevent the spread of face masks is to maintain good personal hygiene, i.e. wash hands frequently and avoid touching the face with hands. Wear a mask only if you have symptoms of respiratory disease such as cough or runny nose.

Those of us, myself included, who have experienced the tight control of segregation within China are naturally worried by this passage. But after more understanding, I feel Singapore so "wide control" behind, there is a very careful consideration.

First of all, scientific research found that CPV is not resistant to high temperature and high humidity environment. Singapore's annual temperature above 30 degrees, humidity is up to 80%-90% . Therefore, the activity of the virus has been greatly reduced, and the spreading harmfulness is much lower than that of the domestic winter environment. This is the first premise of Singapore's policy of "easing" .

Moreover, there is no effective treatment for the virus. So-called cure basically depends on individual antibody to kill virus. The effective treatment means of the hospital is to help specific vulnerable people to control the impact of other complications of the virus. Therefore, the mild symptoms of patients and suspected patients at home isolation, through close contact with the hospital timely feedback, the effect will not make any difference. Singaporeans have a reputation for being law-abiding, and most people don't run around spreading the virus in isolation, so you can trust that. There is already a secondary system for medical treatment in Singapore. People who have minor illnesses go to private clinics. To go to a large hospital, apart from emergency cases, they must first make an appointment with a doctor in a private clinic. This effectively alleviates the resource shortage of large hospitals. In a particular outbreak, this system should be maintained to ensure the most efficient use of effective medical resources. That's why we don't accept mild cases.

As for not "encouraging" wearing a mask, it is a helpless act. Face masks are really in short supply in the current market and can only be given priority to medical workers. At the beginning of February, the Singapore government collected through various channels and distributed four face masks to each household, amounting to more than 5 million, which was a small but insufficient amount of effort.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Masks issued by the Singapore government state that healthy people do not need to wear masks

Interestingly, during an internal meeting between Singapore's Minister of Trade and Industry, Chen Zhensheng, and the Chinese General Chamber of Commerce on February 18, he privately complained about the incident: Some residents asked me, "what if I don't have enough face masks for my family of five? " Chen replied, "Only when you're sick, " Chen said. "What if five people get sick at the same time? " "Then the whole family will be sent to the hospital for treatment and isolation, and you won't even need to use your four masks. "

It's a joke. It's a joke. But Chen pointed out that even if there are tens of millions of masks, it is far from enough, and medical staff should be given priority to get protection. The country should remain calm, be rational, and think long-term, to deal with the economic difficulties that may follow. It's all true, really.

In fact, Singapore's epidemic prevention and treatment work is very meticulous and responsible. The Department of Health will look at the history of transmission of each confirmed case in detail, how it was contracted, who it was exposed to, where it was visited, trying to figure out, and making contact with as many people as possible who the patient had close contact with, put them in quarantine. Check their vitals. Information is available to the public on the Ministry of Health's website to keep people abreast of the latest developments. Such meticulous work, which is seldom reported by foreign media, is an important measure to ensure the safety and control of the epidemic in Singapore.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Singapore's National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID) is responsible for receiving and treating confirmed cases

Today, China's domestic epidemic has gradually entered the second half, but the outbreak in many countries in the world, Singapore's confirmed cases also rose to 212(March 14 data) , the situation is still serious.

My family's day-to-day life in Singapore went on as normal, seemingly unaffected. I still often think back to a time when a family of three were sitting on a bus in Shanghai: The national epidemic had just begun, and the atmosphere was a little tense, but in the car, my daughter is still innocently humming "what a wonderful world" . I think of myself while listening to the young voice, while looking out the window at night scene, feeling extremely. Small children can be left alone and carefree, but it's not easy for US adults to be able to live a stable life in difficult times, thanks to the painstaking efforts of many behind the scenes. It is because of these thoughtful and detailed measures that people like me, who live in Singapore, can live as normal a life as possible and face the epidemic with peace of mind. I think the situation in Singapore is still optimistic and manageable, and I am confident that we can pull through.
